              [bold]Written evidence submitted by [bold]BIS[bold] Sustainability Champion[bold]&#xa0;
[normal]The committee were keen to see the formal terms of reference of both my role as BIS sustainability champion and the recently formed BIS sustainability committee which I chair. These terms of reference are attached at Annex A.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]The committee also asked whether sustainability training was provided by BIS. As my answer on the day indicated, the department does not provide bespoke sustainability training to staff. However, training is available for staff involved in the policy making process, for example on how to construct impact assessment drawing on HMT’s green book. This includes reference to the need to consider economic, social and environmental impacts. DECC run modules on a variety of aspects of carbon, climate change and energy, which are open to all civil servants. I also understand that DEFRA are working with civil service learning to develop an e-learning module on sustainability. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]I also include a copy of the Regional Growth Fund application form. The form is attached at Annex B (an
[normal]d has been sent electronically)
[normal] The guidance for the document is embedded electronically by hovering over the specific questions. The relevant question in this case is I02, where the following pop-up appears “e.g. benefits to the environment, improvements to transport networks and journey times, scientific advances”. The application form itself is designed to be light touch and is therefore deliberately concise. However, applicants are expected to submit a supporting document alongside their bid in which they articulate the case for supporting their bid. As my colleague, Alex Wilson, said in giving evidence to the committee, the overarching objective of the appraisal, in line with HMT green book guidance, is to fairly set out all of the costs and benefits of each project on an appropriately discounted and risk adjusted basis. 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]Finally, I attach a copy of all eleven sector strategies as well as the analysis paper published on 11 September alongside the Industrial Strategy Summit.
[normal] 
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]&#xa0;
